Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have severe consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to properly regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of bipartisan support.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to guide us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I had already heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of the economic advisory staff for US President Bill Clinton, and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was the topic.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a high price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments, when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker, after he had tamed inflation, a second term.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he pursued deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting goals are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always clearly articulated, but sharply differing views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to the populist frenzy).
From my perspective, Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
In addition, we know that traditionally only during tense labor markets are marginalized groups integrated into the economy and wage differences reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every US Federal Reserve chairman.
Already now, the US is facing difficult decisions on how to combat inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially just a problem caused by an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which has still not reached its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and thus an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself as a remedy?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities with asset-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of a stronger and more pervasive mispricing associated with climate-related assets.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump, thereby risking the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have already identified it as the central issue of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not within the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
Ensuring financial stability is part of the Fed's mandate, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record in this area suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy currently needs.
An obvious lack of competition and the absence of sufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant actors more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
Yet every student in their second year would have known that during a recession, one must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argued, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the Federal Reserve Board regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade has been marked by a series of misjudgments that date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Fed's concern, it is a fact that the Bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early rate hike can stifle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal over trading activities by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the administration of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer deciding when certain stock trades would appear inappropriate.
The Fed is somewhat similar to the US Supreme Court.
This body is supposed to stand above politics, but ever since Bush v. Gore, we know that is not the case.
Trump has made this clear for all who still had doubts.
Even the Federal Reserve is supposed to be independent, however Powell and Greenspan, by following their party's deregulation agenda, have clearly shown that this is not the case either.
Yet while the Federal Reserve Board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power has traditionally been concentrated in the hands of the Federal Reserve Chair – much more so than with the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Federal Reserve Chair who decides what comes up for discussion and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example where it is extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The US needs a Federal Reserve that genuinely commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Those who believe that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack insight.
We do not need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
We need someone who has deep understanding of economics and who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden does not need to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated his abilities.
Lael Brainard is already sitting on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her competence and won the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a Federal Reserve Chair who maintains continuity and does not disturb the markets, but who also shares his economic and social agenda.
